**Refining Button Functionality**

I've pinpointed the file; the "Squad Roster" page resides in `components/SquadStatsView.tsx`. The squad list, passed as a prop, requires a new state variable to control the sort order. I'm now exploring the best practices for implementing a click handler on a button element, to modify the state variable that dictates the sort, triggering a re-render. I'm considering using a hook to manage the sort state.


**Considering Sort Logic**

I've examined how `squad` is utilized within `SquadStatsView`. The current implementation maps directly over the provided prop.  To enable local sorting, I'll introduce a state variable. I'm choosing whether to sort the display directly or create a sorted copy.  It seems persisting the sort order would require a function in the parent component. I'm focusing on creating an on-click handler for the button to control sorting through the new state.


**Refining Sorting Implementation**

I'm now leaning toward "Plan A" for UI simplicity. My focus shifts to state management within `SquadStatsView`. I've added a state variable, `sortOrder`, to control ascending, descending, or no sort. The next step is crafting the button's click handler to toggle this state. I'll dynamically sort the `squad` data based on `sortOrder` before rendering the table. I will see if this will suffice, or if persisting sort order should be implemented later.


**Developing Sort UI**

I've added the `sortOrder` state and computed `sortedSquad`. Implementing a button to toggle between 'original' and 'asc' order is next, ideally above the player table for clear access. I'm prioritizing user experience and simplicity with this initial approach.


**Positioning the Sort Button**

I'm now contemplating the placement of the sort button within the `SquadStatsView`. The current layout is a grid, with the roster list residing in a white card on the right. I'm considering placing the "Sort A-Z" button either within the table header itself or in a dedicated header bar above the table. I believe this will enhance user clarity. The code changes required are simple. I've begun working in `components/SquadStatsView.tsx`. I believe a dedicated header bar will look best.


**Adding Sort Toggle**

Now, I'm working with the `Dashboard` and `App` files to ensure they handle the squad data correctly. I've integrated `useState` and `useMemo`, created `isSorted` and the derived `displaySquad`. I am putting the sort button into a `<div>` right before the roster list.


**Implementing the Sort Button**

I've crafted a functional button component within `SquadStatsView.tsx`, which toggles the sort order using the `setIsSorted` function.  It displays either "Sort A-Z" or "Reset Order" based on the `isSorted` state. I've placed the button within a `div` right before the roster list. Now I'll add a header for the list!


**Refining Sort Toggle**

I'm now implementing the `useMemo` hook to sort the squad. I have added a new state variable, `sortAscending`, to track the sort order. The ternary expression elegantly controls the sort logic based on `sortAscending`. I have placed the button for sorting. It simply toggles this `sortAscending` state. I am confident that this is a great approach.


**Refactoring for Clarity**

I'm now revising my approach to the table and sorting to improve clarity. I'm focusing on the `roster` data and removing some of the `squad` naming. The table code seems fine, but `useMemo` is already used for `careerStats`. I'll adapt the logic within `useMemo` to include the `roster`, ensuring the sort logic is handled correctly. I also want to address that the user will want a sort button; I will ensure the button is obvious to the user.


**Optimizing Data Display**

I'm now integrating `sortedSquad` into the table render. Replacing `squad.map` with `sortedSquad.map` is the immediate focus. Preserving `careerStats` calculation integrity is a priority. I'm choosing the header bar approach for the sort button, floating it above the roster list. The UI layout will be as clear as possible.

```tsx
export const SquadStatsView: React.FC<SquadStatsViewProps> = ({ squad, isLoading }) => {
  const [sortAscending, setSortAscending] = useState(false);

  const sortedSquad = useMemo(() => {
    if (!squad) return [];
    const sorted = [...squad]; // Create a copy to avoid mutating the original
    if (sortAscending) {
      sorted.sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));
    }
    return sorted;
  }, [squad, sortAscending]);

  const toggleSort = () => {
    setSortAscending(!sortAscending);
  };

  if (isLoading) {
    return (
      <div className="flex justify-center items-center h-full">
        <LoadingIcon />
      </div>
    );
  }

  return (
    <div className="lg:col-span-2">
      <div className="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div className="flex justify-between items-center p-4">
          <h2 className="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800">Squad Roster</h2>
          <button
            onClick={toggleSort}
            className="px-3 py-1 bg-gray-200 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-300 transition duration-200"
          >
            {sortAscending ? 'Reset Order' : 'Sort A-Z'}
          </button>
        </div>
        <table className="w-full text-sm text-left rtl:text-right text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">
          <thead className="text-xs text-gray-700 uppercase bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400">
            <tr>
              <th scope="col" className="px-6 py-3">
                Name
              </th>
              <th scope="col" className="px-6 py-3">
                Career Stats
              </th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {sortedSquad.map((player) => {
              const careerStats = player.stats.reduce(
                (acc, stat) => {
                  acc.goals += stat.goals;
                  acc.assists += stat.assists;
                  return acc;
                },
                { goals: 0, assists: 0 },
              );

              return (
                <tr key={player.id} className="bg-white border-b dark:bg-gray-800 dark:border-gray-700 hover:bg-gray-50 dark:hover:bg-gray-600">
                  <th scope="row" className="px-6 py-4 font-medium text-gray-900 whitespace-nowrap dark:text-white">
                    {player.name}
                  </th>
                  <td className="px-6 py-4">
                    {careerStats.goals} goals, {careerStats.assists} assists
                  </td>
                </tr>
              );
            })}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};
```


**Implementing Final Sort Logic**

I've integrated `displaySquad` into the table, using `displaySquad.map` in the render function. The sort toggle utilizes `setIsSorted` effectively.  I implemented a button for sorting and the current design is a success. I'm satisfied that a 'Secondary' Button fits well here.


**Adding Button Style Refinement**

Now, I'm integrating the `Secondary` button style from `Button.tsx`.  I'm changing the existing button to leverage that styling.  I am choosing the `bg-gray-200` background for the button.  It's fitting here. I'm focusing on consistency in button styles throughout the app.

